h  He was a man of letters  and he was a man of tremendous principle  His wife said he had this innate ability to make people want to play for him  and those guys really wanted to do well for him  That  in itself  is a mystery  one even the players cannot explain  McKenna was smart  and he was a motivator  At the same time  however  he was  as Ross explains in the foreword  a man who ruled with an  iron fist   He wasn t a ranter and raver at all  said Strickler   But  what he said went  and nobody questioned it   The players  feared the man  but they all respected him   He was preparing these guys for later in life  and what these guys knew later on was the discipline he taught them    The way that he did it prepared them for hardships  Strickler added   That s why they have so much respect for this man  And that is why they have remained so loyal  Two of his former players  Tom Daniel  60 and Howard Moss  60  first approached VMI s superintendent  Gen  J H  Binford Peay III  62  about a book about McKenna several years ago  and Best Regrets is the result  a book that Lazenby says is  a good look at what a football coach ought to be   All of the players who played for him  all of the people who were inspired by him wanted to have his story told  the author said   He was a great  great coach  He was the perfect coach for VMI  To order Best Regrets  visit www vmialumni org McKennaChristmas    Chris Floyd  VMI      What a Football Coach Ought to Be   Best Regrets  chronicles John McKenna s life and his time as the winningest VMI football coach  New Book Describes Esteemed Coach John McKenna and His Era LEXINGTON  Va  Dec  5  2014  John McKenna has long been considered a legend on post at VMI  Now he is being immortalized  Roland Lazenby  74 recently co wrote a book with veteran sports writer Mike Ashley about the winningest coach in VMI football history  Best Regrets chronicles McKenna s life and his 13 years on the VMI sideline  when he led the Keydets to six straight