nt to play for him  and those guys really wanted to do well for him  That  in itself  is a mystery  one even the players cannot explain  McKenna was smart  and he was a motivator  At the same time  however  he was  as Ross explains in the foreword  a man who ruled with an  iron fist   He wasn t a ranter and raver at all  said Strickler   But  what he said went  and nobody questioned it   The players  feared the man  but they all respected him   He was preparing these guys for later in life  and what these guys knew later on was the discipline he taught them    The way that he did it prepared them for hardships  Strickler added   That s why they have so much respect for this man  And that is why they have remained so loyal  Two of his former players  Tom Daniel  60 and Howard Moss  60  first approached VMI s superintendent  Gen  J H  Binford Peay III  62  about a book about McKenna several years ago  and Best Regrets is the result  a book that Lazenby says is  a good look at what a football coach ought to be   All of the players who played for him  all of the people who were inspired by him wanted to have his story told  the author said   He was a great  great coach  He was the perfect coach for VMI  To order Best Regrets  visit www vmialumni org McKennaChristmas     Best Regrets           Best Regrets                     Best Regrets www vmialumni org McKennaChristmas Chris Floyd Chris Floyd VMI VMI Foundation Keydet Club Alumni Webcams Directories My VMI VMI Foundation Keydet Club Alumni VMI Foundation VMI Foundation Keydet Club Keydet Club Alumni Alumni Webcams Directories My VMI Webcams Webcams Directories Directories My VMI My VMI RESOURCES   Title IX  Health   Safety   IT   Site Index Parents   Families   Cadets   Non discrimination Statement   Privacy   THE VMI PHILOSOPHY The VMI experience is framed by relevant education within a military environment  It s an education that develops character  fosters a lifelong appreciation of physical fitness engenders a se